38:27.672 --> 38:30.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are things that are good
for the bottom
line for major companies.

38:30.441 --> 38:33.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Throw in some more military
spending, maybe
some infrastructure spending,
that's good

38:33.678 --> 38:35.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for the bottom line for
corporate America.

38:35.580 --> 38:39.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Add in also, this is a global
economy the
is kind of getting on its feet
after a rough

38:39.484 --> 38:41.986 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
couple of years, rough patch.

38:42.086 --> 38:46.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you combine those things
into one period
of a few months, and that's how
you get these

38:46.157 --> 38:47.926 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
kinds of rallies that we have
seen.

38:48.026 --> 38:50.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: As you say,
Donald Trump
certainly would like to take
credit and has

38:50.495 --> 38:51.996 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
taken credit for this.

38:52.096 --> 38:53.965 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Does he deserve credit for this?

38:54.065 --> 38:57.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: Yes, there is no
question that
the Trump agenda is something
that's making

38:57.635 --> 39:01.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stock investors confident,
that's leading
them to believe that after-tax
profits, which

39:01.206 --> 39:04.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is what matters if you're a
stock investor,
are going to be on the rise in
the years ahead.

39:04.542 --> 39:06.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some of the math is pretty
simple.

39:06.511 --> 39:10.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you're a bank and you can --
your capital
requirements gets dropped, if
you're a military

39:11.015 --> 39:14.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
contractor and your military
spending gets
increased, that is going to go
straight to

39:14.152 --> 39:15.520 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
your bottom line.

39:15.620 --> 39:17.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Lower taxes, good for the bottom
line . That's
all good for stocks.

39:17.622 --> 39:19.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there's no question that's
part of the
Trump agenda.

39:19.891 --> 39:22.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, that said, most of those
policies haven't
actually happened yet.

39:22.560 --> 39:25.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there is still the question
of, will the
Trump administration deliver the
things that

39:25.997 --> 39:26.965 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Wall Street is now expecting?

39:27.065 --> 39:28.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It's an
anticipatory effect.

39:28.600 --> 39:30.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NEIL IRWIN: Exactly.

39:30.501 --> 39:33.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: You wrote
recently that
the real question is, how much
slack is there

39:33.771 --> 39:35.173 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the economy?

39:35.273 --> 39:37.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do you mean by slack, and
why is that
important?

39:38.042 --> 39:41.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: Every economy, every
country has
some kind of economic speed
limit.

39:41.846 --> 39:42.847 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's only so many people.

39:42.947 --> 39:44.983 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They can only produce so much
stuff.

39:45.083 --> 39:49.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question for the economy is
how close
we are to that speed limit in
the United States.

39:49.287 --> 39:50.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How low can the unemployment
rate go?

39:50.989 --> 39:55.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How many more -- how much unused
capacity
is there in the manufacturing
sector?

39:55.159 --> 39:57.028 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that's the big question
going forward.

39:57.128 --> 40:00.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is there room for the economy to
grow 3 percent
or 4 percent, like Donald Trump
said he wanted

40:00.331 --> 40:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to see during the campaign?

40:02.267 --> 40:05.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Or are we pretty much as fast as
we can -- are
we growing as fast as we can,
something like

40:05.870 --> 40:07.739 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
2 percent?

40:07.839 --> 40:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's the big question of
whether this
kind of outstanding growth that
is being priced

40:10.575 --> 40:13.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
into financial markets really
can be delivered
in the years ahead.

40:13.511 --> 40:15.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Do you know
the answer to
that question?

40:15.747 --> 40:17.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If you had to guess, where are
we?

40:17.548 --> 40:18.650 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: We're getting close.

40:18.750 --> 40:20.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Look, we're at under 5 percent
unemployment.

40:20.351 --> 40:23.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, there's a lot of people
outside the labor
market who might come back in.

40:23.688 --> 40:25.390 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So there is some slack out
there.

40:25.490 --> 40:28.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is some room to grow, but
probably not
as much as there was a year or
two ago.

40:28.860 --> 40:32.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that will become the binding
constraint
in these next couple of years.

40:32.563 --> 40:36.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A booming
market is certainly
great if you're in that market,
but not all

40:36.367 --> 40:38.803 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sectors are booming equally.

40:38.903 --> 40:45.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How does this booming market
translate, though,
for people -- does it add to
growth that makes

40:45.109 --> 40:47.111 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a real impact in people's lives?

40:47.211 --> 40:52.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: Look, stock wealth
is held predominantly
by the affluent, so the
distributional effects

40:52.684 --> 40:57.488 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of a higher stock market are
definitely not
even across the population.

40:57.588 --> 41:02.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That said, to the degree that a
higher stock
market, a rising sense of
confidence in corporate

41:02.226 --> 41:05.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
America leads to more hiring,
more capital
expenditures, that can have
broad impacts.

41:06.097 --> 41:10.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there is reason -- if these
numbers hold
up, if what markets are pricing
in, in the

41:11.035 --> 41:15.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump administration actually
happens, that's
a good sign for growth, for job
growth, for

41:15.573 --> 41:17.342 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
expansion of all kinds of
businesses.

41:17.442 --> 41:22.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Given this
economy and what
you know of Trump's proposed
policies, what

41:22.880 --> 41:26.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
specifically about those
policies are you
looking most closely at?

41:26.617 --> 41:28.286 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NEIL IRWIN: I think it's
execution.

41:28.386 --> 41:31.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this big corporate income tax
cut that
the president says he wants to
see, is that

41:31.656 --> 41:32.657 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
really going to happen?

41:32.757 --> 41:33.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How soon will it happen?

41:34.025 --> 41:35.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How big will it be?

41:35.860 --> 41:41.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the regulatory front, how
much of the shift
away from regulation really will
be things

41:41.299 --> 41:42.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that benefit corporate America?

41:43.000 --> 41:45.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How much -- is there going to be
new infrastructure
spending?

41:45.570 --> 41:46.471 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He wants a trillion dollars.

41:46.571 --> 41:47.939 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is that actually going to
happen?

41:48.039 --> 41:49.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Congress isn't so sure.

41:49.941 --> 41:52.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So seeing if some of these
things go from
an idea on a chalkboard to
actual legislation,

41:52.877 --> 41:54.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actual policy, that's the big
question right
now.

41:54.879 --> 41:58.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I know you're
an analyst
and an economics writer, and you
don't buy

41:59.083 --> 42:04.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and sell stocks, but if you had
to be advising
me, do you think this rally is
going to continue?

42:04.355 --> 42:05.656 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Can it keep up like this?

42:05.757 --> 42:07.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NEIL IRWIN: Look, stocks are
priced for protection
right now.

42:07.158 --> 42:09.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're very -- they're highly
priced relative
to earnings.

42:10.061 --> 42:10.962 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's all prospective.

42:11.062 --> 42:12.430 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you're not buying current
earnings.

42:12.530 --> 42:13.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You're buying the future.

42:13.731 --> 42:16.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the future is as uncertain
as it's ever
been.

42:16.634 --> 42:20.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That said, is there plenty of
reason to think
that earnings could grow as the
market is

42:20.805 --> 42:21.706 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
now predicting?

42:21.806 --> 42:23.141 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Certainly.

42:23.241 --> 42:25.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To count on it, think it's
assured makes it
a bit of a risky bet.

42:25.343 --> 42:29.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Neil Irwin of
The New York Times, thank you
very much.

42:29.180 --> 42:35.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NEIL IRWIN: Thank you.

42:35.353 --> 42:41.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: This April
marks 100 years
since the United States joined
the side of

42:41.626 --> 42:43.528 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Allies in World War I.

42:43.628 --> 42:49.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Great War wasn't only joined
in the trenches,
but in the culture in different
ways as well.

42:49.233 --> 42:54.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
An exhibit in Philadelphia
explores how American
artists grappled with a divisive
conflict

42:54.405 --> 42:57.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that produced powerful images
for and against
it.

42:57.909 --> 42:59.544 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

42:59.644 --> 43:05.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I Want You, about
as direct
as it gets, an iconic image from
World War

43:05.349 --> 43:07.218 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
I.

43:07.318 --> 43:11.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The Flower of Death, an
evocative title for
a painting by an American
soldier named Claggett

43:11.122 --> 43:15.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Wilson, that captures some of
the close-up
horror of the war.

43:15.726 --> 43:21.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just some of the ways American
artists responded
to a cataclysmic,
world-shattering and -shaping

43:21.132 --> 43:26.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
event, the subject of a major
new exhibition
at the Pennsylvania Academy of
Fine Arts in

43:26.804 --> 43:30.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Philadelphia titled World War I
and American
Art.

43:30.741 --> 43:32.210 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Co-curator Robert Cozzolino:

43:32.310 --> 43:35.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT COZZOLINO, Co-Curator: At
heart, this
is a human interest story.

43:35.546 --> 43:37.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You mean the
whole war, as
big as it was?

43:37.482 --> 43:43.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT COZZOLINO: You have these
artists who
are thinking, basically, here's
this huge

43:43.354 --> 43:45.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
global conflict going on.

43:45.189 --> 43:46.958 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How do I make sense of it?

43:47.058 --> 43:53.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And how do I also bring it down
to a human
level and express either
dissent, an urgency

43:53.965 --> 43:59.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for America to take part in it,
or to just
express what's at stake?

43:59.737 --> 44:05.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The Great War
began in Europe
in 1914.

44:05.276 --> 44:10.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. didn't join until three
years later,
after an intense public debate
over entering

44:10.715 --> 44:12.183 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a foreign conflict.

44:12.283 --> 44:15.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Artists weighed in on both
sides.

44:15.419 --> 44:22.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
John Sloan's After the War, a
Medal, Maybe
a Job in 1914 was one of the
earliest anti-war

44:22.460 --> 44:23.361 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
drawings.

44:23.461 --> 44:25.229 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Marsden Hartley was conflicted.

44:25.329 --> 44:29.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He lived in Germany and fell in
love with
a German military officer killed
in the war,

44:30.067 --> 44:32.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who Hartley depicted in a series
of paintings.

44:32.970 --> 44:38.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Childe Hassam on the other hand,
active in
the pro-interventionist movement
in New York,

44:38.442 --> 44:42.480 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
streamed flags across his
canvasses in support
of the allies.

44:42.580 --> 44:47.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And George Bellows, an early
opponent of the
war, was moved to support it by
a U.S. government

44:47.785 --> 44:50.855 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
report, later disputed, of
German atrocities.

44:50.955 --> 44:54.091 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT COZZOLINO: He's swayed
that he has
to show what happened.

44:54.191 --> 44:57.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And he swayed,
big time, because
this is an atrocity painting,
right, on a

44:57.862 --> 44:59.730 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
large scale.

44:59.830 --> 45:01.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT COZZOLINO: Yes, he makes
these history
paintings about this
contemporary event, and

45:01.432 --> 45:06.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he's showing the brutality of
these atrocities
being committed to citizens.

45:06.203 --> 45:08.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's showing it at its most
visceral.

45:08.172 --> 45:12.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: More directly,
the U.S. government
commissioned artists to create
propaganda

45:12.276 --> 45:18.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
posters as part of an agency to
influence
public opinion, calls to enlist
in the military,

45:18.215 --> 45:22.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and invest in the war effort,
questioning
the masculinity of fighting age
men, and the

45:23.020 --> 45:25.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
consequences of inaction.

45:25.222 --> 45:27.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Anne Classen Knutson is another
of the show's
curators.

45:27.692 --> 45:30.194 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ANNE CLASSEN KNUTSON,
Co-Curator: You have
seen this image a hundred
different times,

45:30.294 --> 45:31.195 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and this is where it begins.

45:31.295 --> 45:33.064 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

45:33.164 --> 45:36.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE CLASSEN KNUTSON: James
Montgomery Flagg,
a famous illustrator, created
Uncle Sam.

45:36.267 --> 45:42.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He loved himself so much, he
created Uncle
Sam in his own visage, so this
is James Montgomery

45:42.473 --> 45:43.374 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Flagg as Uncle Sam.

45:43.474 --> 45:44.375 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Oh, really?

45:44.475 --> 45:46.077 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANNE CLASSEN KNUTSON: "I want
you."

45:46.177 --> 45:48.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was so well-known, it was
reused over
and over again in the 20th
century.

45:48.446 --> 45:51.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right next to it,
though, a
very different kind of image.

45:51.849 --> 45:55.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE CLASSEN KNUTSON: One of the
subtexts
of this, people before the war
were very worried

45:55.920 --> 45:58.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that immigrants were going to
come -- and
these are not my words -- these
are their

45:58.589 --> 46:03.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
words -- and dilute our white
American bloodlines.

46:03.461 --> 46:05.796 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So this is an image of that,
that fear of
immigrants.

46:05.896 --> 46:08.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Immigrants, and
also African-Americans,
I assume.

46:08.165 --> 46:11.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNE CLASSEN KNUTSON: Also using
-- Tarzan
was a hot topic at the time.

46:12.036 --> 46:15.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The novels were coming out, and
he was using
caricatures of African-
Americans as well.

46:15.339 --> 46:18.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they were very feared during
the war and
not treated well.

46:18.142 --> 46:23.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Other work from
the era countered
that imagery, showing a
normalized, patriotic

46:23.147 --> 46:27.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
black life in a culture that
continued to
discriminate against it.

46:27.151 --> 46:29.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Kelli Morgan is a curatorial
fellow with academy.

46:29.487 --> 46:31.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KELLI MORGAN, Pennsylvania
Academy of Fine
Arts: We have families.

46:31.989 --> 46:39.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
African-American people are,
like I said,
a very integral piece of the
American fabric,

46:39.230 --> 46:41.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that we are meant to be here.

46:41.966 --> 46:44.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is our country, just as
